# Implementation of prims algorithm and graph generation in C++.

Classes - encapsulation of data along with methods that act on them
access specifiers - public and private, all private fields can only be accessed by methods of the class and are not available for acess by using the object.
public methods and variables can be accessed through object of the class.
Constructors - If not defined C++ creates a default constructor for the class, if a constructor is defined than the default constructor is overloaded, multiple constructors
with different signatures can be defined. Compiler and run time will use the one with matching signature.
Destructor - Unlike overloaded constructors, there can only be one destructor - it should free any heap based memory owned by the object, destructor 
takes no arguments.
STL - consist of a trio of - containers, algorithms and iterators. There are two types of containers, namely sequential and associative. Vcetors and lists are example 
of sequential containers, map is an example of an associative container.
input and output streams can be chained, ie the "<<" and ">>" operators are overloaded for stream objects and return a object of type stream. A class can overload 
this operator and abstract the actual display semantics of the object on stdout.

prompting user to enter details about the graph characteristics.
